    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>To Heal the Poor of the World</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Dr Fikry B Salib says pharmaceutial companies should realize that with world growing smaller through air travel, all human beings are prone to same infectious diseases</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Profit-driven enterprises don't  have the incentives to solve some of the world's problems (front page, May 21). A possible solution in the case of pharmaceutical companies, which are very profitable, is to tax  all patent-protected drugs to create an international fund to supply life-saving medications for those who cannot afford them.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Profit-driven enterprises don't  have the incentives to solve some of the world's problems (front page, May 21). A possible solution in the case of pharmaceutical companies, which are very profitable, is to tax  all patent-protected drugs to create an international fund to supply life-saving medications for those who cannot afford them.</p>
        <p>Manufacturers that prefer to opt out could do so, but they would forfeit the protectionist advantage of the patent.</p>
        <p>ROBERT I. MISHELL, M.D.  Berkeley, Calif., May 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
